st for the sake of higher values and commitments. While self-sacrifice has great potential moral value, it can also be used to justify the most brutal acts. Halbertal attempts to unravel the relationship between self-sacrifice and violence, arguing that misguided self-sacrifice is far more problematic than exaggerated self-love. In his exploration of the positive and negative dimensions of self-sacrifice, Halbertal also addresses the role of past sacrifice in obligating future generations and in creating a bond for political associations, and considers the function of the modern state as a sacrificial community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aSacrifice. 0aSelf-sacrifice. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aChristianity.  aGod.  aJewish life.  aJudaism.  aPaul Kahn.  aWestern religious life.  aagent-relative actions.  aattentiveness.  acategorical imperative.  acharity.  acivilians.  acompetition.  acooperation.  adependency.  aethical life.  aethics.  aevolutionary biology.  aexchange.  ageneral will.  agolden rule.  aheroic sacrifices.  ahumans.  aindividuals.  ainstrumental relationship.  alaws of war.  alove.  aloyalty.  amartyr.  amodern state.  amoral sphere.  aoriginal position.  aother.  apast sacrifice.  apolitical bond.  apolitical life.  apolitical order.  apolitical violence.  apolitics.  aprayer.  apsychoanalysis.  areligion.  areligious life.  areliigous communities.  aretroactive desecration.  aritual.  asacrifice.  asacrificial community.  asacrificial system.  asacrificing for.  aself-interest.  aself-sacrifice.  aself-transcendence.  aself.  asocial contract.  asoldiers.  asovereign.  astate.  asuffering.  atemple worship.  autilitarianism.  aviolence.  awar.